04275nam a22007335i 9781501701962DE-B159720190904122446.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190904s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017019627 a10.7591/97815017019622doi  a(DE-B1597)534221  a(OCoLC)1121057296  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHT1523b.B58 2002 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a305.82211 aBlum, Lawrence, eauthor.11a"I'm Not a Racist, But..." :bThe Moral Quandary of Race /cLawrence Blum. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. "Racism": Its Core Meaning -- t2. Can Blacks Be Racist? -- t3. Varieties of Racial Ills -- t4. Racial Discrimination and Color Blindness -- t5. "Race": What We Mean and What We Think We Mean -- t6. "Race": A Brief History, with Moral Implications -- t7. Do Races Exist? -- t8. Racialized Groups and Social Constructions -- t9. Should We Try to Give Up Race? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNot all racial incidents are racist incidents, Lawrence Blum says. "We need a more varied and nuanced moral vocabulary for talking about the arena of race. We should not be faced with a choice of 'racism' or nothing." Use of the word "racism" is pervasive: An article about the NAACP's criticism of television networks for casting too few "minority" actors in lead roles asks, "Is television a racist institution?" A white girl in Virginia says it is racist for her African-American teacher to wear African attire.Blum argues that a growing tendency to castigate as "racism" everything that goes wrong in the racial domain reduces the term's power to evoke moral outrage. In "I'm Not a Racist, But...", Blum develops a historically grounded account of racism as the deeply morally-charged notion it has become. He addresses the question whether people of color can be racist, defines types of racism, and identifies debased and inappropriate usages of the term. Though racial insensitivity, racial anxiety, racial ignorance and racial injustice are, in his view, not "racism," they are racial ills that should elicit moral concern.Blum argues that "race" itself, even when not serving distinct racial malfeasance, is a morally destructive idea, implying moral distance and unequal worth. History and genetic science reveal both the avoidability and the falsity of the idea of race. Blum argues that we can give up the idea of race, but must recognize that racial groups' historical and social experience has been shaped by having been treated as if they were races.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Sep 2019) 0aRace discrimination. 0aRacismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSocial ethics. 4aAfrican-American Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501701962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501701962.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG